    <item>
      <title>Arr stack - Installation</title>
      <link>//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-arr-stack/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 08 Aug 2025 14:45:38 +1000</pubDate>
      <guid>//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-arr-stack/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Part of series on Arr-stack:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-arr-stack/&#34;&gt;Arr-Stack Installation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-arr-stack-configuration/&#34;&gt;Arr-Stack Configuration&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;introduction&#34;&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The &amp;ldquo;arr stack&amp;rdquo; is a popular collection of applications used for managing media libraries. By running these applications as &lt;strong&gt;rootless containers&lt;/strong&gt; with Podman, you can enhance security by preventing the containers from having root privileges on the host machine.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This guide will walk you through setting up the arr stack, including &lt;strong&gt;Jellyfin&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Jellyseerr&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Prowlarr&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Sonarr&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;Radarr&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;Transmission&lt;/strong&gt; as rootless containers. We will cover directory preparation, mounting an external hard drive, and configuring the services using a &lt;code&gt;podman-compose.yaml&lt;/code&gt; file.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Podman 101 - Always Run Rootless!</title>
      <link>//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-101/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 08 Aug 2025 14:45:07 +1000</pubDate>
      <guid>//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-101/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-introduction&#34;&gt;1. Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Podman is a daemonless container engine for running OCI containers.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;It can run as &lt;strong&gt;root&lt;/strong&gt; (rootful) or as a &lt;strong&gt;non-root user&lt;/strong&gt; (rootless), each with different privileges and security implications.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1590497008432-598f04441de8?q=80&amp;amp;w=2891&amp;amp;auto=format&amp;amp;fit=crop&amp;amp;ixlib=rb-4.1.0&amp;amp;ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxwaG90by1wYWdlfHx8fGVufDB8fHx8fA%3D%3D&#34; alt=&#34;container&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;table&gt;&#xA;  &lt;thead&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Feature&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Rootful Podman (Run as root)&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Rootless Podman (Run as non-root)&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/thead&gt;&#xA;  &lt;tbody&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Privileges&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Full root privileges on host system (&lt;code&gt;sudo podman ...&lt;/code&gt;).&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Limited to user’s privileges (&lt;code&gt;podman ...&lt;/code&gt;).&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Security&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Compromised container could gain root on host.&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Limited damage — container root maps to non-root UID on host.&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Networking&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Can bind to privileged ports (&amp;lt;1024) directly.&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Uses &lt;code&gt;slirp4netns&lt;/code&gt;, cannot bind &amp;lt;1024 without extra config.&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;User ID Mapping&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Container root = Host root.&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td style=&#34;text-align: left&#34;&gt;Container root maps to non-root UID.&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/tbody&gt;&#xA;&lt;/table&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-running-rootless&#34;&gt;2. Running Rootless&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Do &lt;strong&gt;not&lt;/strong&gt; use &lt;code&gt;sudo&lt;/code&gt; to start containers.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Arr Stack - Configuration</title>
      <link>//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-arr-stack-configuration/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 08 Aug 2025 17:18:26 +1000</pubDate>
      <guid>//localhost:1313/hidden/podman-arr-stack-configuration/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;introduction&#34;&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The &amp;ldquo;Arr stack&amp;rdquo; is a popular set of applications for automating your media library. This blog post will walk you through configuring a basic Arr stack using &lt;strong&gt;Podman&lt;/strong&gt; on your homelab. We&amp;rsquo;ll cover &lt;strong&gt;Jellyfin&lt;/strong&gt; for media streaming, &lt;strong&gt;Jellyserr&lt;/strong&gt; for integrating services, &lt;strong&gt;Prowlarr&lt;/strong&gt; for managing indexers, and &lt;strong&gt;Sonarr&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Radarr&lt;/strong&gt; for automating TV and movie downloads. This setup provides a simple yet powerful way to manage your media. 🚀&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;configuring-the-arr-stack&#34;&gt;Configuring the Arr Stack&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Basic flow about how each service talks to each other&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
